>>127661955
Not really, original dishes are few and far between. Native culture is mostly lost as there was a long war, and besides the natives mostly ate just roasted meat. The only native foods that are still commonly consumed are mate and locro I think. We do have our spin on the recipes immigrants brought though, sometimes with spices native to the land which ig adds some originality. Most of what we eat is meat and pasta, all edible parts of the animals are eaten besides reproductive organs. Vinaigrette tongue sandwiches, blood sausages, roasted intestines, boiled stomach, brain puree, etc. Also there's lots of varieties in meat, about half of the country by area eats more lamb than beef, venison is very common everywhere but the north, seafood, pork, rabbit, etc. The only unique non-native Argentine foods that come to mind right now are sandwiches de miga and dulce de leche. Also pastries are very common as we drink lots of mate, many are unique to here but I don't know their names, we just call them pastelitos or facturas based on how they look. There are also sweets called dulce de membrillo and dulce de batata, which I think originate here. The only things I'm confident could be rated amongst the best of the world are our wines and ice creams.
I get the impression my other comments came across as if I defend Argentina's place on the list, which I don't, no country in the Americas deserve a place in the first page except maybe Mexico and Peru, as they kept more of their native dishes. I think the only reason Argentina, America and Brasil are where they are is because you can easily find dishes from LOTS of other countries, either authentic or with a local innovation.

La Repubblica recounts how the 38-year-old Italian defender was called to discuss the case with the prosecutors back on April 4, where he was reminded of the need to be entirely honest when speaking about the situation.

Juventus have been accused of secretly paying their players during the early stages of the COVID pandemic despite publicly announcing that four months’ worth of salary payments had been waivered.

Initial questions were mostly simple and set the scene, asking him when he joined the club, his relationship with the management and how much his salary was. He also discussed the role of his brother Claudio in Turin.

Discussing the start of the situation, he said: “When the pandemic broke out, clearly a period of panic and economic difficulty, I was asked to act as a go-between with the rest of the group to meet the extraordinary moment that had been created.

Chiellini then revealed that, after a few conversations with Andrea Agnelli and Fabio Paratici, “what was done was to waive four monthly payments to allow the club to breathe with the promise, that when the season resumed, based on what would happen, a part would be returned.

The reason why football is better than any other sport out there is because anyone can succeed regardless of how they were born. For the past 15 years now, people have been debating Messi vs Ronaldo, but they couldn't be more different when you truly look at them closely. One is shorter and weaker, but highly gifted technically, the other is taller and stronger, but less gifted technically. They both succeeded and reached heights never reached before in the sport. Those traits caused them to develop playstyles that are widely different from one another. Both should be appreciated.

Is it right to discredit the greats of the sport, just because you want to discredit Ronaldo's poaching playstyle that he developed in his later years? Gerd Muller, Inzaghi, Batistuta, Romario, Butragueno Van Nistlerooy all had legendary legendary poaching ability or were poachers themselves. Poaching is a style that requires a high IQ and understanding of the game. It's why Halaand scores so many goals, because he knows how to read the game and where to be. Poaching is nothing to look down upon, it's a very valid playstyle, and I'm kind of disappointed to see so many people here not appreciating it.
